|||| GENERAL: OVERVIEW

   The way this tool works is by scanning specifically typed names of JSON files in the same directory as the GST script
 this script (at the current version) has 4 stages:
  -Initialization
  -Creation
  -Painting
  -Display

  Initialization:  Initialization is the stage where the program loads all imports and necessary JSON files to run (rules.json)
  it's a pretty short period and it's main purpose is in it's name

  Creation: Creation is where Graphs are initialized and it's where the bulk of the logic is,although at the current version
  creation only consists of the use_preset mode,which is limited to user-pre-made files.

  Painting: This is the stage where the preperation for Display happens and the bulk of this stage is painting nodes
  using either heatmaps or user-defined functions

  Display: This is arguably the biggest part of the code,this is where all the logging happens,with all statistics and such
  plus this is where the graphs are displayed on your screen

  This 4 Stages are segregated inorder to better organize the codebase and restrict the amount of bug-hunting time,
  this also offers the chance for people to mod the tool and add extra steps to this pipeline,instead of being a jungled mess
  of hardcoded-junk

  Now this is only one part of the system,the other two parts are the
   -Painting Module (PM)
   -Importance Algorithm Module (IAM)

  The painting module is the most flexible part of the codebase,allowing for any user to modify,add and generally play around
  with the way data is being represented on their screen,i encourage alot of tampering,both in the JSON AND the Python files.
  it's generally a very crucial part of the system,as without it,you cannot have a meaningful representation of data.

  The Importance Algorithm on the other hand is a more subjective module,it allows for people to add Algorithms to determine the
  "importance" of any node at a given graph,in combination with the Painting Module,they provide crucial information on how
  "safe" your graphs are.

  Lastly,the rules.json
  This file is where all the rules for the program reside and i disencourage messing around with the file too much or modding it
  as it can be a bit problematic at times.



