   Step 1:
    Creating a Graph

   You can create a Graph by copying the Template.json and adding you own nodes/vertices & connections/edges
   but what does each value do?
   lets see here...
   {
  "directed": false,
  "algorithm": "spring",
  "V": ["Bob","Josh","Mary"],
  "E": [
      ["Bob","Josh"]
      ,["Josh","Mary"]
      ,["Mary","Bob"]
      ]
    }

  directed -> it specifies whether the graph is a Directed Graph,or a Undirected Graph (DG & UG for short)
  algorithm -> specifies which algorithm to use when positioning the nodes
  usable algorithms:

  -arf
  -bipartite
  -bfs
  -circular
  -forceatlas2
  -kamada_kawai
  -planar
  -random
  -shell
  -spring
  -spiral

   The best ones to use (in my humble opinion) are "kamada_kawai" and "planar" BUT if you want a default one for all use-cases,use "spring"

   V -> this is the list of vertices you can add to your graph,currently,due to not having built some type of converter,most people (unless you make a converter)
   have to fill this in by hand

   E -> Same with V But the difference is it stores the EDGES of the graph ("connections"),withouth those,your nodes are lonely


   That's it about hte Graph JSON,pretty simple


